WEBVTT

00:02.819 --> 00:04.753
♪ ♪

00:21.413 --> 00:22.688
(Bob groans)

00:22.915 --> 00:24.523
You're a little groan-ier
than usual this morning, Dad.

00:24.750 --> 00:27.175
(yawns) I didn't sleep great
last night.

00:27.194 --> 00:28.527
Yeah, look at your eyes.

00:28.696 --> 00:31.012
The airlines would charge you
extra for those bags.

00:31.090 --> 00:32.272
Why couldn't you sleep?

00:32.441 --> 00:33.515
Were you thinking about
all the regrets you have?

00:33.683 --> 00:34.941
So many, I'm guessing.

00:35.094 --> 00:36.976
Yeah, but also, sometimes

00:37.129 --> 00:38.945
your mom can get a little kicky.

00:39.098 --> 00:40.205
Oh, no, was I kicking?

00:40.357 --> 00:42.357
A little. A lot. Very hard.

00:42.451 --> 00:44.543
Well, I was dreaming
that I was a flapper.

00:44.694 --> 00:45.952
And you kicked Dad in his flaps?

00:46.105 --> 00:47.195
-Sorry, hon.
-I mean,

00:47.289 --> 00:48.455
I'm tired, but it's fine.

00:48.607 --> 00:50.532
I'll just drink coffee
pretty much all day.

00:50.551 --> 00:51.533
That's healthy, right?

00:51.552 --> 00:52.793
Yup, totally. Hey, guys,

00:52.945 --> 00:54.369
does anyone have a bunch
of extra shelves

00:54.388 --> 00:55.870
-they want to give me?
-LINDA: Why?

00:55.890 --> 00:58.373
'Cause I am going to be winning
a ton of prizes at school

00:58.467 --> 01:00.208
and I'm gonna need a place
to put them all.

01:00.286 --> 01:02.394
We're starting a special unit
on ancient Greece today,

01:02.546 --> 01:06.214
and I hear Ms. Padaro is pretty
generous with the "prizolas."

01:06.233 --> 01:08.716
She really is. Who do you think
I got my mood ring from?

01:08.811 --> 01:11.295
-It was from her.
-Yeah, that unit
was the highlight

01:11.313 --> 01:12.796
of my fourth grade.
Well, that and winning

01:12.815 --> 01:15.132
the long-distance pee-pee
contest in the boys' room,

01:15.150 --> 01:17.892
but I didn't win for accuracy,
I won for artistry.

01:17.912 --> 01:19.136
Also, I was alone.

01:19.229 --> 01:20.579
Louise, I think you're
gonna like Ms. Padaro.

01:20.730 --> 01:22.414
You learn all about
the Greek gods and goddesses

01:22.641 --> 01:23.990
and how annoyed they always were
with everyone.

01:24.159 --> 01:26.752
Yeah, just learning the steps to
becoming a god would be great.

01:26.903 --> 01:29.479
You can be whatever you set
your mind to be, sweetie.

01:29.481 --> 01:31.906
Right, but maybe
not a Greek god?

01:32.075 --> 01:34.501
Maybe not, maybe yes.
Who knows, Bob?

01:34.653 --> 01:37.654
Don't squash her dreams,
you puny human man.

01:37.673 --> 01:39.005
I'm gonna strike him down first.

01:39.100 --> 01:40.006
BOB:
Mm.

01:40.101 --> 01:41.749
So Greece-y in here.

01:41.844 --> 01:44.661
I'm sitting next to Louise.
I'm sitting next to Louise.

01:44.830 --> 01:46.271
And I'm sitting next to you.

01:46.498 --> 01:48.014
Okay, so, for the next
two weeks,

01:48.167 --> 01:49.424
you are ancient Greeks,

01:49.593 --> 01:52.185
and you will sit in the round,
as the Greeks did.

01:52.338 --> 01:54.780
Doesn't it feel more equal,
more democratic?

01:55.007 --> 01:56.615
Well, guess who
invented democracy.

01:56.692 --> 01:57.674
Miss America?

01:57.693 --> 02:00.010
-David Democracy?
-Santa Claus?

02:00.028 --> 02:01.787
Uh, no, but good guesses.

02:01.938 --> 02:03.771
Um, the ancient Greeks
invented it.

02:03.866 --> 02:06.458
Did you hear Ms. Padaro has
a bunch of prizes you can win?

02:06.610 --> 02:07.609
Oh, I've heard.

02:07.628 --> 02:09.353
When is she gonna talk
about the coins?

02:09.371 --> 02:10.537
I know, right?

02:10.631 --> 02:11.946
I have a question
about the coins and prizes.

02:12.040 --> 02:13.132
That's my question.

02:13.359 --> 02:14.967
-(overlapping chatter)
-Okay, okay.

02:15.118 --> 02:16.860
I will be quizzing you
throughout the unit,

02:16.879 --> 02:20.288
and if you give the right
answer, you get one of these.

02:20.382 --> 02:21.214
Nice.

02:21.367 --> 02:22.716
I made these clay replicas

02:22.885 --> 02:24.868
of ancient Greek coins,
and you can

02:24.961 --> 02:26.979
trade them in
for prizes at this...

02:27.130 --> 02:28.538
-market.
-STUDENTS: Whoa!

02:28.557 --> 02:29.648
Prizes.

02:29.875 --> 02:31.299
They look like they're
from the dollar store,

02:31.318 --> 02:32.893
so you know they're expensive.

02:33.045 --> 02:34.544
It might finally be time
for me to take a whack

02:34.563 --> 02:36.380
at this class
participation thing.

02:36.398 --> 02:39.883
Also, at the end of the unit,
we'll have a huge symposium,

02:39.902 --> 02:40.993
aka party.

02:41.162 --> 02:44.070
The god Dionysus will keep
the grape juice flowing.

02:44.239 --> 02:45.647
-(all exclaiming)
-Oh, man!

02:45.741 --> 02:49.001
All right, who can tell me
what that building is? Chloe.

02:49.228 --> 02:50.502
-The Parthenon?
-Correct.

02:50.654 --> 02:51.653
Whoa.

02:51.839 --> 02:54.247
And the Parthenon
is part of a larger group

02:54.400 --> 02:56.675
of historic buildings
called the...

02:56.902 --> 02:57.734
-(students straining)
-Tommy.

02:57.753 --> 02:59.178
-The Acropolis?
-Correct.

02:59.329 --> 03:00.737
In the round? (scoffs)

03:00.906 --> 03:02.681
More like she should
turn around, am I right? Sheesh.

03:02.850 --> 03:04.533
She's being a real circle jerk.

03:04.668 --> 03:07.001
Next question, I'm just gonna
jump on her like a backpack.

03:07.021 --> 03:09.079
<i> LINDA:</i>
<i> All right, I'm calling it.</i>

03:09.097 --> 03:11.005
-Good night, sweetie.
-Good night, Lin.

03:11.099 --> 03:13.433
(sighs, snoring)

03:13.602 --> 03:15.585
-(grunting)
-Ow.

03:15.679 --> 03:17.178
Oh, my God, that was quick.

03:17.347 --> 03:19.105
Is she Charleston-ing?

03:19.274 --> 03:22.117
Ow. Ow. (sighs) All right.

03:23.370 --> 03:25.370
Oh, hey, Gene.
What-what are you doing up?

03:25.522 --> 03:27.781
Hello, Father. I think
I might need some nachos.

03:27.933 --> 03:30.600
No, Gene. No nachos.
Go back to sleep.

03:30.694 --> 03:32.436
Also, I don't think
we have stuff for nachos.

03:32.438 --> 03:34.213
Not with that attitude. Hold on.

03:34.364 --> 03:36.289
If you're sleeping on the couch,
that means...

03:36.366 --> 03:37.865
I could have
a sleepover at Mom's.

03:37.885 --> 03:40.201
Am I dreaming or did I hear
sleepover at Mom's?

03:40.221 --> 03:41.869
-Yup. It's on.
-Yes!

03:41.889 --> 03:44.798
You guys, seriously, be careful.
She's really kicky tonight.

03:44.892 --> 03:46.450
Oh, she wouldn't kick her kids.

03:46.468 --> 03:49.043
-She loves us.
-Is it a sleepover at Mom's?

03:49.137 --> 03:50.971
-Yup.
-(yawns) May as well.

03:51.065 --> 03:54.566
LINDA:
Aw, sleepover at Mom's?
All right!

03:54.718 --> 03:56.793
-GENE: But with
lingering Dad smell.
-Mm.

03:56.812 --> 03:58.219
<i> LOUISE:</i>
<i> Okay,</i>

03:58.239 --> 04:00.239
Chloe and Kaylee got
called on a bunch yesterday.

04:00.466 --> 04:01.965
Maybe we try to sit
where they sat?

04:01.984 --> 04:03.575
Yeah, I want to sit
in the splash zone,

04:03.727 --> 04:05.059
but for answering questions.

04:05.228 --> 04:06.970
-Hey!
-Oh, sorry.

04:06.989 --> 04:10.323
-Um, this is my seat.
-It was your seat yesterday.

04:10.476 --> 04:12.734
Now you can go sit
in no-coins-ville.

04:12.753 --> 04:13.901
But they're all good seats.

04:14.070 --> 04:15.645
That's the beauty
of sitting in the round.

04:15.739 --> 04:17.163
Well, it's just that, yesterday,

04:17.258 --> 04:19.424
this seat got a lot of action,
and not so much over there.

04:19.501 --> 04:21.743
Let's just stay in the same
seats. Keeps things simple,

04:21.911 --> 04:24.004
but don't worry, Louise,
I see all,

04:24.156 --> 04:25.913
like the many-eyed giant, Argos.

04:25.933 --> 04:27.507
Thankfully, I don't have
that many eyes,

04:27.659 --> 04:29.601
or I'd spend
a fortune on contacts.

04:29.753 --> 04:33.438
Anyway, who knows what monster
Argos slayed? Louise.

04:33.665 --> 04:36.758
Oh... Well, I don't know
the answer to that one.

04:36.777 --> 04:40.779
Kind of skimmed the Argos stuff.
I'm gonna say Godzilla?

04:40.930 --> 04:42.172
Oh, no. Tommy.

04:42.341 --> 04:43.931
-Echidna?
-Correct.

04:44.026 --> 04:45.358
-(groans)
-Correct.

04:45.511 --> 04:47.769
-Correct. Correct.
-Dang it.

04:47.863 --> 04:49.863
The lady just doesn't see us.
It's not fair.

04:50.032 --> 04:52.349
She's like a shopping cart
with a wobbly wheel,

04:52.367 --> 04:54.442
-she just pulls to the right.
-I hate those shopping carts.

04:54.536 --> 04:57.779
Okay, the marketplace
is open for business.

04:57.947 --> 05:00.465
-Time to cash in those coins.
-Yes!

05:00.617 --> 05:02.375
I'm gonna get that eraser
that looks like a foot.

05:02.469 --> 05:05.211
I'm gonna get a temporary
tattoo. Take that, Mom.

05:05.364 --> 05:06.954
And I'm just gonna watch
everyone else

05:07.049 --> 05:10.033
-get cool things, I guess.
-This is some B.S.

05:10.126 --> 05:11.977
Some serious B.S.

05:12.204 --> 05:13.961
Some super serious B.S.

05:13.981 --> 05:15.314
If I don't get
that windup dolphin

05:15.465 --> 05:17.482
that actually swims
in a bathtub...

05:17.634 --> 05:19.634
I don't even want to think
about it. (grunts)

05:19.653 --> 05:21.711
Hey, does punching a locker
hurt your hand?

05:21.805 --> 05:24.548
-Probably. Eh, forget it.
-We got to do something.

05:24.566 --> 05:26.066
We could offer her
American cash money.

05:26.160 --> 05:27.993
I have $10 in my dad's wallet.

05:28.144 --> 05:31.312
Or... we could...
make clay coins ourselves.

05:31.332 --> 05:32.998
To... make ourselves
feel better?

05:33.225 --> 05:34.816
No, to use in class.

05:34.835 --> 05:39.004
We make our own replica coins
of Ms. Padaro's replica coins.

05:39.231 --> 05:40.672
You mean like counterfeiting?

05:40.899 --> 05:42.232
I saw that in a movie
that I wasn't supposed to watch

05:42.325 --> 05:43.416
that I watched five times.

05:43.585 --> 05:45.569
Yeah, technically,
it's counterfeiting,

05:45.587 --> 05:47.346
but look, we tried playing by
the rules, and it didn't work.

05:47.514 --> 05:50.164
What are we gonna do?
Not get coins and cool prizes?

05:50.258 --> 05:51.683
-You make a good point.
-I do.

05:51.835 --> 05:55.579
So, who's in for making our
own coins and our own justice?

05:55.597 --> 05:57.505
We're only in
fourth grade once, baby.

05:57.599 --> 05:59.173
-Plus, I'll do anything you do.
-Rudy?

05:59.342 --> 06:01.342
Count-erfeit me in. Man,

06:01.436 --> 06:02.844
this is the coolest
I've ever felt,

06:02.921 --> 06:05.697
and saying that out loud
made it less cool. Sorry. Sorry.

06:09.761 --> 06:12.095
Louise, don't you usually sit
with Gene and Tina at lunch?

06:12.114 --> 06:13.597
Rudy, this is a top secret

06:13.615 --> 06:15.949
counterfeiting
brainstorming session.

06:16.043 --> 06:17.376
I can't trust
those blabber butts.

06:17.561 --> 06:18.935
I told them you were
going through a crisis,

06:19.028 --> 06:20.545
and you needed
special lunch counseling.

06:20.697 --> 06:22.530
Why am I the one who needs
special lunch counseling?

06:22.699 --> 06:23.623
I'm fine.

06:23.717 --> 06:26.276
-Poor Rudy. He looks terrible.
-Mm-hmm.

06:26.369 --> 06:27.794
Okay, first thing's first,

06:27.888 --> 06:29.279
we got to make a mold
of a clay coin.

06:29.372 --> 06:30.947
How the H are we gonna do that?

06:30.966 --> 06:33.450
-Millie, can I have
a piece of gum?
-From my mouth or fresh?

06:33.468 --> 06:35.285
-How about fresh.
-Weird, but okay.

06:35.378 --> 06:37.211
Rudy, you got a quarter
or a nickel or something?

06:37.231 --> 06:40.399
If I had a nickel for every time
you asked me for a quarter...

06:40.626 --> 06:42.550
-Uh, sorry. Here you go.
-(spits)

06:42.569 --> 06:44.903
RUDY:
I hope you're gonna
wipe that off.

06:45.054 --> 06:46.646
Now, you see the impression
this makes? If this gum

06:46.798 --> 06:49.074
was a hard mold, we could
press clay in there,

06:49.225 --> 06:51.317
and it would be
the exact shape of a quarter.

06:51.470 --> 06:53.561
So, all we need
is some gold-colored clay,

06:53.655 --> 06:56.397
a hard mold, and one
of Ms. Padaro's coins.

06:56.417 --> 06:58.491
-And the blood of a virgin.
-What's a virgin?

06:58.644 --> 07:01.086
I think it's someone
who gives a lot of blood.

07:01.163 --> 07:02.904
Oh. My grandfather's a virgin.

07:02.998 --> 07:05.815
I love TV,
and if you're about to say,

07:05.834 --> 07:07.150
"Well, then
why don't you marry it?"

07:07.169 --> 07:08.576
you should know
that we're engaged.

07:08.595 --> 07:10.411
All right, my family.
It's getting late.

07:10.431 --> 07:11.988
-Time for bed.
-You know, I actually

07:12.007 --> 07:13.915
slept really well last night
here on the couch.

07:13.934 --> 07:15.583
Um, I think I'm gonna
do that again.

07:15.602 --> 07:18.678
Aw, okay, Mr. Couching Tiger,
Sleeping Dragon.

07:18.830 --> 07:21.498
You kids want to have
another sleepover at Mom's?

07:21.591 --> 07:24.000
-Yeah!
-Hmm, let me check my schedule.

07:24.093 --> 07:25.351
Just kidding. I'm available.

07:25.446 --> 07:26.853
You guys didn't get
kicked last night?

07:27.005 --> 07:28.947
Of course I'm not gonna
kick them, Bob. They're my kids.

07:29.207 --> 07:31.524
Well, actually you did,
a little, but it felt nice.

07:31.618 --> 07:34.360
-It was like shiatsu.
-I'm gonna take a rain check.

07:34.455 --> 07:37.104
Got to rest up for
ancient Greece class tomorrow

07:37.166 --> 07:38.682
because I'm a good student.

07:38.700 --> 07:41.460
Wow. Our great parenting
just started to work,

07:41.611 --> 07:44.204
with one of you. The rest of you
little delinquents come with me.

07:44.298 --> 07:46.706
-Yay!
-Hey, we can play
"Never Have I Ever."

07:46.800 --> 07:50.302
I'll start. Never have I ever
played "Never Have I Ever."

07:50.529 --> 07:53.579
(humming)
♪<i> Making my cozy bed.</i> ♪

07:53.640 --> 07:57.124
Oh, right, books. People like
to read those before bed.

07:57.293 --> 07:59.719
<i> Pepper: A Spicy History.</i>

07:59.871 --> 08:00.812
Okay. All right.

08:01.039 --> 08:03.206
Oh, this is nice.

08:03.299 --> 08:05.466
This is very, very nice.

08:05.486 --> 08:08.044
"Forget everything
you know about pepper."

08:08.213 --> 08:09.470
(yawns) Okay.

08:09.490 --> 08:12.549
That might be enough
reading for tonight.

08:12.567 --> 08:14.034
<i> LOUISE:</i>
<i> All right,</i>

08:14.219 --> 08:15.309
let's get that coin. Ms. Padaro,

08:15.329 --> 08:18.330
may I be excused
to visit the restroom?

08:18.481 --> 08:19.981
-Of course.
-Thank you.

08:20.000 --> 08:22.667
So, today, I'd like
to get into the gods

08:22.819 --> 08:23.576
and Mount Olympus.

08:23.670 --> 08:25.987
Um, I don't want
to alarm anyone,

08:26.006 --> 08:27.839
but there's a mouse over there!

08:27.991 --> 08:29.749
(gasps) I see it, too.

08:29.843 --> 08:33.178
I don't see it. Do you know
what a mouse looks like?

08:33.329 --> 08:34.754
RUDY:
Oh, my gosh, it was right there.

08:34.906 --> 08:35.997
-Keep looking.
-Yeah, yeah.

08:36.016 --> 08:37.240
Keep looking in that direction

08:37.333 --> 08:38.517
-and no-no other direction.
-Huh.

08:38.668 --> 08:40.852
Weird, yeah.
He must've scurried away.

08:41.004 --> 08:44.022
Sorry. And... take us back
to Greece.

08:44.766 --> 08:45.915
(grunts)

08:46.009 --> 08:47.526
A moldy but a goodie.

08:47.602 --> 08:50.011
-MS. PADARO: And Zeus
was pretty mad...
-(screams)

08:50.105 --> 08:52.513
The mouse is back! Everyone look

08:52.533 --> 08:53.848
with your eyes.

08:53.942 --> 08:56.109
And... he's gone again.

08:56.261 --> 08:58.278
-Weirdest thing.
-(sighs) Classic mouse.

08:58.430 --> 09:01.373
Coming and going
whenever it wants.

09:02.450 --> 09:04.450
I can't believe I slept
through the night last night.

09:04.545 --> 09:06.044
I mean, that's
what nights are for.

09:06.195 --> 09:07.287
No, y-you don't understand.

09:07.439 --> 09:08.880
This might be the first time

09:09.032 --> 09:11.407
I've slept all the way through
the night in possibly 15 years.

09:11.459 --> 09:13.218
Is-is this how
regular people feel?

09:13.387 --> 09:15.053
I don't know,
but you do look radiant.

09:15.204 --> 09:16.446
-I feel radiant.
-(door bells jingle)

09:16.464 --> 09:18.464
-Hi, kids.
-Hey, Mom.
-Hey-o.

09:18.617 --> 09:20.374
Uh, hey. I have
a little group project

09:20.468 --> 09:21.876
to do with Rudy and Millie.

09:21.895 --> 09:24.896
Is it okay if we go upstairs?
We really need to focus.

09:25.048 --> 09:26.547
-Uh, sure.
-I don't remember

09:26.641 --> 09:29.067
doing a group project
for the ancient Greek unit.

09:29.218 --> 09:30.384
-Do you?
-The younger generation

09:30.404 --> 09:32.979
just lives in another world,
don't they?

09:33.131 --> 09:34.480
Okay, we have our mold.

09:34.633 --> 09:37.634
We have our gold clay.
The oven is preheating.

09:37.727 --> 09:39.319
Let's make some money, people.

09:39.471 --> 09:41.246
-I'm in her room.
-We can hear you.

09:41.397 --> 09:42.639
-No, you can't.
-(grunts)

09:42.657 --> 09:44.307
LOUISE:
Come to mama.

09:44.400 --> 09:46.751
-Oh...
-She's beautiful.

09:46.903 --> 09:48.645
Bake, you little fakies.

09:48.663 --> 09:50.422
<i> LINDA:</i>
♪<i> Slumber party dance party,</i>
<i> lying down in bed</i> ♪

09:50.573 --> 09:52.832
-♪<i> Pew, pew, pew, pew</i> ♪
-(vocalizing)

09:52.909 --> 09:55.093
LINDA: ♪<i> Slumber party dance</i>
<i> party, lying down in bed...</i> ♪

09:55.320 --> 09:58.004
Mm. Where else can I go
that's quiet? Oh.

09:58.098 --> 09:59.839
This could work.

09:59.933 --> 10:01.766
<i> MS. PADARO:</i>
<i> So, the Socratic method</i>

10:01.918 --> 10:05.103
is about asking questions
and challenging assumptions.

10:05.330 --> 10:06.271
There's no right answer.

10:06.498 --> 10:08.255
Well, that kind of takes
the pressure off.

10:08.275 --> 10:10.091
Ooh, we better get
to the marketplace.

10:10.110 --> 10:12.093
Yeah, o-okay, sure.
Yeah. All right.

10:12.112 --> 10:14.112
Oh, the marketplace you say?

10:14.339 --> 10:15.947
Suppose I could check it out.

10:16.174 --> 10:17.507
(chuckles nervously)

10:17.525 --> 10:19.175
What if she figures out
our coins are fake?

10:19.194 --> 10:21.177
She won't if we just
play it cool.

10:21.196 --> 10:23.179
(inhales deeply)
Take it in.

10:23.181 --> 10:25.181
Don't you just love the danger?

10:25.200 --> 10:26.625
What? No! I don't!

10:26.852 --> 10:29.443
Guys, pull it together.
This is just a test-drive.

10:29.537 --> 10:31.278
We don't want
to set off any alarms.

10:31.298 --> 10:34.023
One small thing each.

10:34.117 --> 10:35.783
Okay, who's next? Louise?

10:35.877 --> 10:38.119
-Yes. Hello.
-RUDY and MILLIE: Hi.

10:38.138 --> 10:40.213
Holy crap, it worked. It worked.

10:40.365 --> 10:42.807
-What a rush.
-Okay, so it's game on.

10:42.959 --> 10:45.727
-Now, I love school.
-I kind of want
to steal a truck.

10:49.875 --> 10:51.483
I could put this sticker
in my locker. I could put this

10:51.634 --> 10:53.151
sticker on my skateboard
if I had a skateboard.

10:53.302 --> 10:54.468
Smell this.
I love eraser smell.

10:54.488 --> 10:56.396
I can't believe
we can make our own coins

10:56.490 --> 10:59.140
-and get whatever we want.
-Guys, I love this stuff, too,

10:59.159 --> 11:01.234
but we got to keep a low profile

11:01.386 --> 11:04.070
and try to get called on
every now and then, okay?

11:04.222 --> 11:05.571
So, what are we gonna do?

11:05.666 --> 11:08.241
-(inhales deeply)
-Never stop buying stuff?
-No.

11:08.393 --> 11:09.501
We're gonna keep a low profile.

11:09.728 --> 11:11.836
No big-ticket items
and no spending sprees.

11:12.063 --> 11:13.730
-Right. Yup. Got it. Yup.
-Okay, great. Great.
Yeah. Got it.

11:13.732 --> 11:15.507
